on**\n\n             Introduction\nMedical images such as X-rays, CTs, and MRIs\nare commonly used to diagnose, monitor, or treat\nmedical conditions in clinical practice (FDA, 2022).\nWith the rapid growth of medical images and the\ncorresponding reports data, researchers have de-\nveloped various deep learning models to support\nclinical decision making (Çallı et al., 2021).\nRecently, large-scale image-text pre-training,\ne.g., CLIP (Radford et al., 2021), has achieved\nconsiderable successes in computer vision and nat-\nural language processing domains. CLIP is trained\nto predict the correct matching of a batch of images\n1Our code is available at https://github.com/\nRyanWangZf/MedCLIP .\n2050100 200 570\n# of thousands of image-text pairs4045505560Zero Shot Accuracy (%)\n(20K, 44.8%)\n(369K, 42.2%)(191K, 43.3%)\n9.6x fewer dataMedCLIP\nConVIRT\nGLoRIAFigure 1: Zero-shot performance of MedCLIP , Con-\nVIRT (Zhang et al., 2020), GLoRIA (Huang et al.,\n2021) when using different amounts of data for pre-\ntraining. ConVIRT and GLoRIA are trained on\nMIMIC-CXR (369K) and CheXpert (191K) dataset, re-\nspectively. Our method yields superior ACC than GLo-\nRIA using near 1=10of pre-training data.\nand text training examples. The joint-training of im-\nage and text representations on large-scale image-\ntext pairs generates transferable representations and\nsupports ﬂexible downstream tasks. Inspired by\nsuccess of CLIP, we believe the knowledge jointly\nlearned from medical images and reports should be\nhelpful for downstream clinical tasks.\nHowever, adopting vision-text pre-training on\nmedical domain is a non-trivial task due to (1)\nCLIP’s (Radford et al., 2021) data-hungry nature:\nCLIP is trained on a dataset of 400M image-text\npairs collected from the internet, while the total\nnumber of publicly available medical images and\nreports is orders of magnitude below; and (2) speci-\nﬁcity of medical images and reports: compared to\ngeneral domains (e.g., "cats" v.s. "dog"), the dif-\nferences within medical domains are more subtle\nand ﬁne-grained (e.g., "pneumonia" v.s. "consoli-\ndation"). In a nutshell, it is necessary to (1) address\nthe data insufﬁciency issue; and (2) capture the\nsubtle yet crucial medical meanings.arXiv:2210.10163v1  [cs.CV]  18 Oct 2022New left lower \nlobe opacity\nsuggestive of left \nlower lobe \npneumonia\nLeft rib fractures \nwith adjacent \nopacity concerning \nfor either pleural or \nextrapleural massAnchor image\nTrue positive False negativeMedical image datasets\nMedical image -text datasetsMedical text datasets\n•pacification of the right hemi thorax consistent\n•increased left bilateral pleural effusion\n•right transjugular swan ganz catheter ends in\nthe right pulmonary artery …\nNegative imageFigure 2: Demonstration of challenges in medical image-text contrastive learning. (1) Pre-training data only\nincludes paired images and texts. However, many more image-only and text-only datasets are ignored. (2) False\nnegatives appear. For an anchor image, previous Results of Image-Text retrieval tasks on CheX-\npert5x200 dataset. We take the Precision@{1,2,5,10}\nto measure the performance of various models in this\ntask. Best within the data are in bold.\nModel P@1 P@2 P@5 P@10\nCLIP 0.21 0.20 0.20 0.19\nConVIRT 0.20 0.20 0.20 0.21\nGLoRIA 0.47 0.47 0.46 0.46\nMedCLIP 0.45 0.49 0.48 0.50\nimage.\nWe display the experiments on four X-ray\ndatasets to answer the following questions:\n•Q1. Does the proposed pre-training method\nyield better zero-shot image recognition perfor-\nmances?\n•Q2.Does the knowledge-driven supervision, i.e.,\nsemantic matching task, facilitate the contrastive\nimage-text pre-training?\n•Q3. Does MedCLIP bring better performance\nand label efﬁciency for downstream classiﬁca-\ntion tasks with ﬁne-tuning?\n•Q4.Are the learned embeddings good at cross-\nmodal retrieval tasks?\n•Q5.How do the learned embeddings look like?\n4.1 Datasets\nCheXpert (Irvin et al., 2019) is a large dataset of\nchest X-rays with 14 observation labels collected\nfrom Stanford Hospital. Note that this dataset does\nnot provide the corresponding medical reports\nto the public. We use the training split\n\n            **Your Task**\n\n            Use only the Introduction above as your literature context. External paper databases, arXiv, author-profile APIs, and web search are not part of this benchmark.\n\n            1. **Context analysis**: Summarize the problem setting, prior approaches mentioned in the Introduction, and implied gaps you can infer from that text alone.\n\n            2. **Brainstorming**: Collaboratively brainstorm potential research ideas that build upon or address gaps in the Introduction.\n\n            3. **Summarization**: Summarize your collective ideas.\n\n            4. **Formulate a New Research Idea**: Develop a new research proposal in the format of the \'5q\', defined below:\n\n               **Here is a high-level summarized insight of a research field Machine Learning.**\n\n               **Here are the five core questions:**\n\n               **[Question 1] - What is the problem?**\n\n               Formulate the specific research question you aim to address. Only output one question and do not include any more information.\n\n               **[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?**\n\n               Explain the broader implications of solving this problem for the research community.\n               Discuss how such a paper will affect future research.\n               Discuss how addressing this question could advance knowledge or lead to practical applications.\n\n               **[Question 3] - Why is it hard?**\n\n               Discuss the challenges and complexities involved in solving this problem.\n               Explain why naive or straightforward approaches may fail.\n               Identify any technical, theoretical, or practical obstacles that need to be overcome. MAKE IT CLEAR.\n\n               **[Question 4] - Why hasn\'t it been solved before?**\n\n               Identify gaps or limitations in previous research or existing solutions.\n               Discuss any barriers that have prevented this problem from being solved until now.\n               Explain how your approach differs from or improves upon prior work. MAKE IT CLEAR.\n\n               **[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**\n\n               Outline your proposed methodology in detail, including the method, dataset, and metrics that you plan to use.\n               Describe the expected outcomes. MAKE IT CLEAR.\n\n            Please work together to produce the \'5q\' for your proposed research idea.\n\n            Good luck!\n            '}, 'task_results': [{'agent_id': 'agent1', 'result': "Result from the model:### Context Analysis\n\n**Problem Setting:**\nThe introduction discusses the use of deep learning models, particularly those inspired by CLIP, for medical image-text pre-training. The goal is to leverage large-scale image-text pairs to generate transferable representations that can support downstream clinical tasks in medical imaging.\n\n**Prior Approaches:**\n- CLIP is a successful model in computer vision and natural language processing, trained on a large dataset of image-text pairs.\n- Models like ConVIRT and GLoRIA have been developed for medical image-text pre-training, but they face challenges due to data insufficiency and the subtle differences in medical images and reports.\n\n**Implied Gaps:**\n1. **Data Insufficiency:** Medical datasets are much smaller compared to general datasets like those used for CLIP.\n2. **Subtle Medical Meanings:** Medical images and reports have fine-grained differences that are more subtle than general images and texts.\n3. **Knowledge-Driven Supervision:** The introduction mentions the need for semantic matching tasks to facilitate contrastive image-text pre-training.\n4. **Cross-Modal Retrieval:** There is a need to improve the performance of learned embeddings in cross-modal retrieval tasks.\n\n### Brainstorming\n\n1. **Enhancing Data Efficiency:**\n   - Develop methods to augment medical image-text datasets.\n   - Use synthetic data generation techniques to increase the size of training datasets.\n\n2. **Semantic Matching Tasks:**\n   - Design new semantic matching tasks that capture the nuances of medical images and reports.\n   - Incorporate domain-specific knowledge into the pre-training process.\n\n3. **Cross-Modal Retrieval:**\n   - Improve the performance of learned embeddings in cross-modal retrieval tasks.\n   - Develop new evaluation metrics that better reflect the performance of medical image-text models.\n\n4. **Domain Generalization:**\n   - Create models that can generalize across different medical domains and datasets.\n   - Develop techniques to improve the robustness of medical image-text models.\n\n### Summarization\n\nThe key gaps identified are data insufficiency, capturing subtle medical meanings, improving semantic matching tasks, and enhancing cross-modal retrieval. Potential research ideas include developing data augmentation techniques, designing new semantic matching tasks, improving cross-modal retrieval, and creating domain-generalizable models.\n\n### Formulate a New Research Idea\n\n**High-level summarized insight of a research field Machine Learning:**\nIn the field of machine learning, particularly in medical image-text pre-training, there is a need to address data insufficiency and capture the subtle nuances of medical images and reports to improve the performance of models in downstream clinical tasks.\n\n**Here are the five core questions:**\n\n**[Question 1] - What is the problem?**\nHow can we improve the performance of medical image-text pre-training models in the face of data insufficiency and subtle medical meanings?\n\n**[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?**\nSolving this problem is crucial for advancing the field of medical imaging and improving clinical decision-making. Better-performing models can lead to more accurate diagnoses and improved patient outcomes.\n\n**[Question 3] - Why is it hard?**\nThe challenges include the limited size of medical datasets, the subtle differences in medical images and reports, and the need for domain-specific knowledge in the pre-training process.\n\n**[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**\nPrevious models have struggled with data insufficiency and capturing subtle medical meanings. There is a need for new techniques and methods to address these challenges.\n\n**[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**\nThe proposed approach includes developing data augmentation techniques, designing new semantic matching tasks, and improving cross-modal retrieval. The expected outcomes are better-performing medical image-text pre-training models that can generalize across different medical domains and datasets. The methodology will involve using medical image-text datasets, employing advanced deep learning models, and evaluating performance using precision, recall, and cross-modal retrieval metrics.\n"}, {'agent_id': 'agent2', 'result': "Result from the model:### Context Analysis\n\n**Problem Setting:**\nThe introduction discusses the use of deep learning models, particularly those inspired by CLIP, for medical image-text pre-training. The goal is to leverage the joint training of image and text representations to improve downstream clinical tasks in medical imaging.\n\n**Prior Approaches:**\n- CLIP is a successful model in computer vision and natural language processing, trained on a large dataset of image-text pairs.\n- Models like ConVIRT and GLoRIA have been developed for medical image-text pre-training, but they face challenges due to data insufficiency and the subtle differences in medical images and reports.\n\n**Implied Gaps:**\n- **Data Insufficiency:** Medical datasets are much smaller compared to the internet datasets used for training CLIP.\n- **Subtle Medical Meanings:** Medical images and reports have fine-grained differences that are more subtle than general domain images and texts.\n- **Knowledge-Driven Supervision:** The introduction mentions the need for semantic matching tasks to facilitate contrastive image-text pre-training.\n\n### Brainstorming\n\n1. **Enhancing Data Efficiency:**\n   - Develop methods to augment medical image-text datasets.\n   - Use synthetic data generation techniques to increase the size of training datasets.\n\n2. **Semantic Matching Tasks:**\n   - Design and implement knowledge-driven supervision tasks to improve contrastive learning.\n   - Explore the use of domain-specific knowledge to enhance the learning process.\n\n3. **Cross-Modal Retrieval:**\n   - Improve the performance of cross-modal retrieval tasks using advanced pre-training techniques.\n   - Develop models that can better understand and match medical images with their corresponding reports.\n\n4. **Fine-Tuning for Downstream Tasks:**\n   - Investigate the effectiveness of fine-tuning pre-trained models for specific clinical tasks.\n   - Explore the use of transfer learning to improve the performance of models on downstream tasks.\n\n### Summarization\n\nThe key gaps identified are data insufficiency, the need for capturing subtle medical meanings, and the importance of knowledge-driven supervision in medical image-text pre-training. Potential research ideas include enhancing data efficiency, designing semantic matching tasks, improving cross-modal retrieval, and fine-tuning models for downstream clinical tasks.\n\n### Formulate a New Research Idea\n\n**High-level summarized insight:**\nThe integration of advanced pre-training techniques with domain-specific knowledge can significantly improve the performance of medical image-text models, addressing the challenges of data insufficiency and subtle medical meanings.\n\n**Here are the five core questions:**\n\n**[Question 1] - What is the problem?**\nHow can we improve the performance of medical image-text pre-training models in the face of data insufficiency and subtle medical meanings?\n\n**[Question 2] - Why is it interesting and important?**\nSolving this problem can lead to more accurate and efficient medical image analysis, improving clinical decision-making and patient outcomes. It will advance the field of medical imaging and contribute to the development of more robust and reliable AI models for healthcare applications.\n\n**[Question 3] - Why is it hard?**\nThe challenges include the limited size of medical datasets, the need for capturing subtle differences in medical images and reports, and the complexity of designing effective knowledge-driven supervision tasks. Naive approaches may fail due to overfitting and the inability to generalize to new data.\n\n**[Question 4] - Why hasn't it been solved before?**\nPrevious research has focused on general domain pre-training techniques, which may not be directly applicable to the medical domain. The specific challenges of medical image-text pre-training, such as data insufficiency and subtle medical meanings, have not been fully addressed.\n\n**[Question 5] - What are the key components of my approach and results?**\nThe proposed approach involves developing a knowledge-driven pre-training framework that incorporates domain-specific semantic matching tasks and data augmentation techniques. The methodology will be evaluated on medical image-text datasets, and the results will be compared to existing models in terms of zero-shot image recognition, cross-modal retrieval, and downstream classification tasks. The expected outcomes include improved performance in these tasks and a more robust and reliable medical image-text model.\n"}, {'agent_id': 'agent3', 'result': 'Result from the model:\nResult from the function:{"success": true, "message": "Successfully completed session 837323f5-6e77-4df6-8a98-29f0145469ad", "full_chat_histor